The genus does not run to any genus in the keys (
Trjapitzin 1989
; 
Noyes et al. 1997
). Extensive morphological comparisons were made with several brachypterous genera (
Trjapitzin and Gordh 1979
); however, 

Globulencyrtus

Hoffer, 1976 differs in the following characteristics: head with sharp occipital margin, clava shorter than funicle, forewing rudiments, and reaching to about apex of scutellum posteriorly (
Hayat et al. 2013
); 

Austrochoreia

Girault, 1929 is distinguished by the elongate pronotum that almost covers the mesoscutum, lack of notaular lines and abbreviated wings (
Noyes and Hayat 1984
); it can be distinguished from 

Aglyptus

(
Tetracneminae
) by several key characteristics: body chocolate-brown-yellow, with light green shine, female body length 1.9-2.0 mm, forewing not developed and with dark transverse band in the apical third; similarly, the related genus 

Bactritopus

with large and deep depression on face, clypeal margin forming a spatulate protrusion, antennal toruli located at the edge of mouth, mandible tridentate, with a long middle tooth, mesoscutum with complete notauli, wings not shortened (
Trjapitzin 1978
). The specimens also share some characteristics with the genus 

Choreia

(
Encyrtinae
), but they differ notably in having a large punctation on the vertex and frons, occipital margin sharp, mesoscutum usually 3
x
as broad as long, scutellum roundish in back view, axillae meeting, and female body length at least 1 mm (
Westwood 1833
; 

Foerster
1856

). We also found some characteristic differences within the new species, the hind margin of T1 slightly incised medially in some individuals.

Female.
Length 0.7 mm. Body black with dark bluish metallic sheen (Fig. 

). Antenna, femora, and tibiae dark brown, head in dorsal view with bronze shine at some angle. Mesosoma black. Legs with all coxae black; trochanter and their apices deep yellow, tarsal segments 1-3 yellow, fourth and fifth tarsi dark brown (Fig. 

). Gaster black except T6-7 dark brown.

Head in frontal view 1.2 x as broad as high (385:330) (Fig.
), 1.9 x as broad as mesosoma, with fine reticulate sculpture, covered with sparse and short setae; frontovertex width 0.5 x head width (117:385), antenna located below the lower eye margin and separated from clypeus margin by 1.4 x height of the torulus, inner edge of eyes diverged at the lower part, malar sulcus distinct and straight, malar space 0.65 x as long as eye height (120:185), mandible bidentate. Head in dorsal view 2.1 x as broad as long (347:168), ocelli forming an obtuse angle (110°), POL 1.8 x as long as OOL (55:30), posterior edge of eye adjacent to posterior margin of head. Antenna with scape cylindrical and covered with short setae, 9 x as long as wide (260:28), pedicel 2 x as long as wide (60:30); all funicular segments longer than wide (Fig.
), each funicular with three rows of irregular longitudinal sensilla, F1 and F3 2 x as long as broad respectively (40:20), obviously shorter than pedicel and other segments, F4-F6 subequal in length, 1.5 x as long as broad (45:30); clava 3-segmented, 3.6 x as long as broad (145:40), longer than the combined length of F5-F6, with obscure boundaries and apically rounded, the collective length of pedicel and flagellum 1.22 x as long as head width (470:385).

Mesosoma much shorter than metasoma and reticulate sculpture larger than that on head. Pronotum 1.8 x as long as mesoscutum length (90:50) and 2.78 x as broad as long (250:90); mesoscutum 5.2 x as wide as long (260:50) (Fig.
), notaular lines absent, tegula large and semicircular; scutellum slightly convex and 2.2 x as wide as long (250:117), scattered with some short white setae irregularly arranged on its posterior part, axillae very small and apically separated; propodeum medially longer than 1/3 of the scutellum (40:117), with sinuated inverted U-shaped ridges (Fig.
). Mesotibial spur strong, 0.6 x as long as basitarsus (63:104) (Fig.
). Wings absent.

Male. Length 0.57-0.64 mm (0.6 +/- 0.042 mm, N = 5) (Fig.
